  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Two and twenty years old",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ahaziah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 22:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " his age is given as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "forty-two",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This cannot be correct, but is due to a misreading of the Hebrew letters which were used as numerals. Jehoram, the father of Ahaziah, was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "thirty-two",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " years old (see verse 17) when he began to reign and he reigned eight years. If Ahaziah was two and twenty at his father’s death, he was born when Jehoram was eighteen. This is not uncommon in the East. Indeed we find from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 22:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that Jehoram had other children older than Ahaziah, but they were slain by the Arabian invaders.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Athaliah, the daughter of Omri",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Athaliah was the daughter of Ahab and Jezebel and so the grand-daughter of Omri. For this manner of speech cf. verse 20 of the next chapter, where Jehu is called the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "son",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of Nimshi, though he has been twice spoken of in previous verses (2, 14) as the son of Jehoshaphat, the son of Nimshi.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 26.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - Two and twenty years old was Ahaziah when he began to reign. The writer of Chronicles says, \"two and forty\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 22:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), which is absolutely impossible, since his father was but forty when he died (see ver. 17, and setup. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 21:5, 20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Even \"two and twenty\" is a more advanced age than we should have expected, since Ahaziah was the youngest of Jehoram's sons (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 21:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); he must therefore have been born in his father's nineteenth year. Yet he had several elder brothers (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 21:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 22:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ")! To explain this, we have to remember ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(1)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the early age at which marriage is contracted in the East (twelve years); and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(2)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the fact that each prince had, besides his wife, several concubines. That Joram had several appears from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 21:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he reigned one year in Jerusalem. And his mother's Ares was Athaliah, the daughter of Omri King of Israel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". There is something very remarkable in the dignity and precedence attached to Omri. He was, no doubt, regarded of a sort of second founder of the kingdom of Israel, having been the first monarch to establish anything like a stable dynasty. His \"statutes\" were looked upon as the fundamental laws of the kingdom, and were \"kept\" down to the time of its destruction (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Micah 6:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Foreigners knew Samaria as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Beth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Khumri",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
